#. HTML: <section class="sutta" id="sn11.22"><article><div class="hgroup"><p class="division">
msgctxt "sn11.22:0.1"
msgid "Saṃyutta Nikāya 11 "
msgstr "Linked Discourses 11 "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn11.22:0.2"
msgid "3. Tatiyavagga "
msgstr "3. The Third Chapter "

#. HTML: </p><h1>
msgctxt "sn11.22:0.3"
msgid "22. Dubbaṇṇiyasutta "
msgstr "22. Ugly "

#. HTML: </h1></div><p>
#. REF: pts2ed1.510, sc1
msgctxt "sn11.22:1.1"
msgid "Sāvatthiyaṃ jetavane. "
msgstr "Near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove. "

msgctxt "sn11.22:1.2"
msgid "Tatra kho … pe … etadavoca: "
msgstr " "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn11.22:1.3"
msgid "“bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, aññataro yakkho dubbaṇṇo okoṭimako sakkassa devānamindassa āsane nisinno ahosi. "
msgstr "“Once upon a time, mendicants, there was a native spirit who was ugly and deformed. He sat on the throne of Sakka, lord of gods. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn11.22:1.4"
msgid "Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, devā tāvatiṃsā ujjhāyanti khiyyanti vipācenti: "
msgstr "But the gods of the Thirty-Three complained, grumbled, and objected, "

msgctxt "sn11.22:1.5"
msgid "‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho. "
msgstr "‘It’s incredible, it’s amazing! "

msgctxt "sn11.22:1.6"
msgid "Ayaṃ yakkho dubbaṇṇo okoṭimako sakkassa devānamindassa āsane nisinno’ti. "
msgstr "This ugly and deformed spirit is sitting on the throne of Sakka, the lord of gods.’ "

msgctxt "sn11.22:1.7"
msgid "Yathā yathā kho, bhikkhave, devā tāvatiṃsā ujjhāyanti khiyyanti vipācenti tathā tathā so yakkho abhirūpataro ceva hoti dassanīyataro ca pāsādikataro ca. "
msgstr "But the more the gods complained, the more attractive, good-looking, and lovely that spirit became. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts1ed1.238, sc2
msgctxt "sn11.22:2.1"
msgid "Atha kho, bhikkhave, devā tāvatiṃsā yena sakko devānamindo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā sakkaṃ devānamindaṃ etadavocuṃ: "
msgstr "So the gods went up to Sakka and told him what had happened, adding, "

msgctxt "sn11.22:2.2"
msgid "‘idha te, mārisa, aññataro yakkho dubbaṇṇo okoṭimako sakkassa devānamindassa āsane nisinno. "
msgstr " "

msgctxt "sn11.22:2.3"
msgid "Tatra sudaṃ, mārisa, devā tāvatiṃsā ujjhāyanti khiyyanti vipācenti: "
msgstr " "

msgctxt "sn11.22:2.4"
msgid "“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho. "
msgstr " "

msgctxt "sn11.22:2.5"
msgid "Ayaṃ yakkho dubbaṇṇo okoṭimako sakkassa devānamindassa āsane nisinno”ti. "
msgstr " "

msgctxt "sn11.22:2.6"
msgid "Yathā yathā kho, mārisa, devā ujjhāyanti khiyyanti vipācenti tathā tathā so yakkho abhirūpataro ceva hoti dassanīyataro ca pāsādikataro cāti. "
msgstr " "

# NOTE: BB treats this line as if spoken by Sakka. MS treats it as concluding the deva’s speech. In this case, MS is correct. When addressing the gods collectively, Sakka uses the plural mārisā (SN 11.3, SN 11.4, SN 11.14, SN 35.248). In addition, the idiom “So hi nūna”, so far as I can tell, always occurs at the start of a new speaker’s statement.
msgctxt "sn11.22:2.7"
msgid "So hi nūna, mārisa, kodhabhakkho yakkho bhavissatī’ti. "
msgstr "‘Surely, good sir, that must be the anger-eating spirit!’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts2ed1.511, sc3
msgctxt "sn11.22:3.1"
msgid "Atha kho, bhikkhave, sakko devānamindo yena so kodhabhakkho yakkho tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā dakkhiṇajāṇumaṇḍalaṃ pathaviyaṃ nihantvā yena so kodhabhakkho yakkho tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tikkhattuṃ nāmaṃ sāveti: "
msgstr "Then Sakka went up to that spirit, arranged his robe over one shoulder, knelt with his right knee on the ground, raised his joined palms toward the anger-eating spirit, and pronounced his name three times: "

msgctxt "sn11.22:3.2"
msgid "‘sakkohaṃ, mārisa, devānamindo, sakkohaṃ, mārisa, devānamindo’ti. "
msgstr "‘Good sir, I am Sakka, lord of gods! Good sir, I am Sakka, the lord of gods!’ "

msgctxt "sn11.22:3.3"
msgid "Yathā yathā kho, bhikkhave, sakko devānamindo nāmaṃ sāvesi tathā tathā so yakkho dubbaṇṇataro ceva ahosi okoṭimakataro ca. "
msgstr "But the more Sakka pronounced his name, the uglier and more deformed the spirit became, "

msgctxt "sn11.22:3.4"
msgid "Dubbaṇṇataro ceva hutvā okoṭimakataro ca tatthevantaradhāyīti. "
msgstr "until eventually it vanished right there. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn11.22:3.5"
msgid "Atha kho, bhikkhave, sakko devānamindo sake āsane nisīditvā deve tāvatiṃse anunayamāno tāyaṃ velāyaṃ imā gāthāyo abhāsi: "
msgstr "Then Sakka, lord of gods, guiding the gods of the Thirty-Three, recited this verse: "

#. HTML: </p><blockquote class="gatha"><p>
#. REF: sc4
msgctxt "sn11.22:4.1"
msgid "‘Na sūpahatacittomhi, "
msgstr "‘My mind isn’t easily upset; "

#. HTML: <br>
msgctxt "sn11.22:4.2"
msgid "nāvattena suvānayo; "
msgstr "I’m not easily drawn into the maelstrom. "

#. HTML: <br>
msgctxt "sn11.22:4.3"
msgid "Na vo cirāhaṃ kujjhāmi, "
msgstr "I don’t get angry for long, "

#. HTML: <br>
msgctxt "sn11.22:4.4"
msgid "kodho mayi nāvatiṭṭhati. "
msgstr "anger doesn’t last in me. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts2ed1.512, sc5
msgctxt "sn11.22:5.1"
msgid "Kuddhāhaṃ na pharusaṃ brūmi, "
msgstr "When I do get angry I don’t speak harshly, "

#. HTML: <br>
msgctxt "sn11.22:5.2"
msgid "Na ca dhammāni kittaye; "
msgstr "nor do I advertise my own virtues. "

#. HTML: <br>
msgctxt "sn11.22:5.3"
msgid "Sanniggaṇhāmi attānaṃ, "
msgstr "I carefully restrain myself "

#. HTML: <br>
msgctxt "sn11.22:5.4"
msgid "Sampassaṃ atthamattano’”ti. "
msgstr "out of regard for my own welfare.’”"

#. HTML: </p></blockquote></article></section></body></html>
